Team A

On this first assignment, applying the basic functions of the Igraph package is required. The following datasets are going to be used:

  • Actors dataset - undirected graph - : For the 2005 Graph Drawing conference a data set was provided of the IMDB movie database. We will use a reduced version of this dataset, which derived all actor-actor collaboration edges where the actors co-starred in at least 2 movies together between 1995 and 2004.

  • Wikipedia Dataset - directed graph - . The vertices of this network are wikipedia pages. The label of each vertex is the title of the wikipedia page. Edges represent hyperlinks between wikipedia pages; that is, if there is an edge from page A to page B, it means that page A has an hyperlink to page B. The dataset is available at: https://www.cs.upc.edu/~CSN/lab/wikipedia.gml

You have to complete the code chunks in this document but also analyze the results, extract insights and describe them in an understandable way.

Please, write all your conclusions in blue.

After loading both datasets and creating the graphs, and using the summary function, we got an UNW- description for Actors. Therefore we can deduce that this graph is (U) Undirected, (N) Named and (W) Weighted. There are 17577 nodes in the network along with 287074 edges. As for the second line,and after merging the 2 actor datasets, the summary function shows the attributes and seperates them by a comma. We have name, main genre, and genres with (v/c) implying vertex attributes with a character types, movies_95_04 as a (v/n) a vertex attribute with numeric type, and weight with (e/n) implying its an edge attribute with a numeric type.

As for the Wikipedia page, we got an D— igraph suggesting that it is (D) Directed. It has 27475 nodes with 85729 edges. It has a wikiid and id (v/n) vertex level attributes with numeric type, and a label (v/c) vertex level attribute of a character attribute.

Degree distribution

Represent the degree distribution of both networks. For directed graphs, compute the total degree distribution considered the graph as undirected, the in-degree distribution and the out-degree distribution. How do these distributions look like? Are they similar? What about their means? And their standard deviations with respect to the mean?

Wikipedia Graph as Undirected total degree distribution

deg <- degree(as.undirected(wikigraph), mode="total")
hist(deg, main="Histogram of Total node degree",xlim=c(0,50), ylim=c(0,8000),breaks = 10000)

deg.dist <- degree_distribution(as.undirected(wikigraph, mode = "collapse"), cumulative=T, mode="total")
plot( x=0:max(deg), y=1-deg.dist, pch=19, cex=1.2, col="orange", 

      xlab="Degree", ylab="Cumulative Frequency for total degree", xlim = c(0,30))

print("Mean total: ")
## [1] "Mean total: "
mean(deg)
## [1] 5.397489
print("Standard Deviation:")
## [1] "Standard Deviation:"
sd(deg)
## [1] 13.06602

In the “histogram of node degree” the frequency shows that the most common nodes have degrees around 1 ot 10. When taking the zoom out and looking at outliers, the graph is most highly right-skewed and exhibiting a long tail distribution, meaning that the large majority of nodes have low degrees but a small number of nodes, known as “hubs”, have high degrees. These outliers are the reason why the mean is 5.397489 and and not a number from 1 to 3 where the big concentration of degrees appear graphically.

After examining the cumulative degree distribution, that shows us the total running of frequencies accumulated, we can observe that after 15 degrees the curve stops increasing and becomes constant, therefore the majority of nodes have from 1 to 10 degrees.

The standard deviation is 13.06602 which is a number more than two times the mean, thus the mean is not an exact representation of all the nodes because of the noise.

Conclusion

The mean of the actor’s social network (32.66473) is larger than that of the the Wikipedia network (5.397489). This implies that on average each node in the actors network has more connections to other nodes. This makes sense since Wikipedia pages are more unlikely to be connected than actors in a movie.

The standard deviation is larger in the actors network (47.63042) than in the Wikipedia network (13.06602). Therefore, the actors network is affected by actors that have a lot of connections (edges) or a high degree. This phenomenon is also the reason why the mean of the actors network is larger than its median.

Network Diameter and Average Path Length

Compare the network diameter and the average path length of both networks. Consider the actors graph as unweighted. Does the Wikipedia graph have a larger diameter than the actors graph? Why? What about the average path length?

Network Diameter

print("wikipedia diameter")
## [1] "wikipedia diameter"
diameter(wikigraph, directed=T)
## [1] 41
print("actors graph diameter")
## [1] "actors graph diameter"
diameter(actors_graph, directed=F, weights=NA)
## [1] 16

We can define the diameter of a network as the longest of all the calculated shortest paths in a network. In this case Wikipedia has the largest path between the farthest nodes, hence a larger diameter.

We can informally suggest that the Wikipedia network has a larger diameter because the pages about topics are more connected to other links since knowledge in a encyclopedia can connect from one topic to an other and so on. Instead, the actors network diameter is usually small since actors usually participate in movies of a certain genre and they usually don’t change genre, thus creating sub-networks

Average Path Length

print("wikipedia average path length")
## [1] "wikipedia average path length"
mean_distance(wikigraph, directed=T)
## [1] 8.285487
print("actors graph average length")
## [1] "actors graph average length"
mean_distance(actors_graph, directed=F)
## [1] 4.890546

The distance between two nodes is defined as the number of edges along the shortest path connecting them. So the average distance is bigger for the wikipedia network meaning that nodes are on average more distant from each other.

The local clustering coefficient, 𝑐𝑙(𝑣), gives for node 𝑣 the proportion of neighbors of 𝑣 that are also connected to each other. The actors social network has a larger average local clustering coefficient because neighbors are more connected to echother that the wikipedia network. In the global clustering coefficient the tendency is the same, meaning that separete sub networks are not affecting the tendency eventhough the difference is not as big as in the local average clustering coefficient

How do you explain the high closeness of the top-20 list? An actor 𝐼 is central in closeness if it can easily interact with all other actors, that is the distance 𝑑(𝑖, 𝑗) to all other actors, where 𝑗 is short. A pattern observed is that some of the links with high betweenness and high degree centrality also happen to have closeness centrality. For example, id 12533 is both, central in closeness and betweenness, and id 8436 is also central in high degree and in closeness. This could suggest that the networks are extremely separated from each other, so the nearest path to connect nodes are through betweenness centrality or largest degree centrality.

Explore the Erdos-Renyi model and compare its structural properties to those of real-world networks (Wikipedia and actors):

## [1] 287074
actor_erg <- erdos.renyi.game(length(V(actors_graph)), length(E(actors_graph)), type = "gnm", directed = FALSE)
degdis_erg <- degree_distribution(actor_erg, cumulative = T, mode='all')
erdos_renyi_actor_deg <- degree(actor_erg)
plot( x=0:max(erdos_renyi_actor_deg ), y=1-degdis_erg , pch=19, cex=1.2, col="orange",

      xlab="Degree", ylab="Cumulative Frequency")

wiki_erg <- erdos.renyi.game(length(V(wikigraph)), length(E(wikigraph)), type = "gnm", directed = TRUE)
degdis_erg <- degree_distribution(wiki_erg, cumulative = T, mode='all')
erdos_renyi_wiki_deg <- degree(wiki_erg)
plot( x=0:max(erdos_renyi_wiki_deg ), y=1-degdis_erg , pch=19, cex=1.2, col="orange",

      xlab="Degree", ylab="Cumulative Frequency")

fastgrredy uses a buttom-up hierarchical approach. It optimizes for modularity in a greedy manner. The modularity of a graph with respect to some division (or vertex types) measures how good the division is, or how separated are the different vertex types from each other. Initially, every vertex belongs to a separate community, and communities are merged iteratively such that each merge is locally optimal (i.e. yields the largest increase in the current value of modularity).

Write a short proposal for your final project.

we found 2 datasets that were of our interest.

first one, Open flights datset, has the following description “The data is downloaded from Openflights.org. Unlike the BTS data, this dataset contains ties between two non-US-based airports. As such, it gives much more of a complete picture and avoids the sample selection. The weights in this network refer to the number of routes between two airports.” 2.9k nodes,30.5k edges. http://networkrepository.com/inf-openflights.php

an Amazon recommendation networks, Description: Network was collected by crawling Amazon website. It is based on Customers Who Bought This Item Also Bought feature of the Amazon website. If a product A is frequently co-purchased with product B and vice-versa (i.e., product B is co-purchased with product A), then graph contains an edge between A and B. 91.8k nodes and 125.7k edges. http://networkrepository.com/rec-amazon.php
